"""
MKT Context Layer — Jeremiah chapters 49–50
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-jeremiah-49-50-fill.py

Ch 49: Oracles Against the Nations — Ammon (1–6), Edom (7–22), Damascus (23–27),
       Kedar/Hazor (28–33), Elam (34–39).
Ch 50: The Great Oracle Against Babylon (all 46 verses).

Key historical anchors:
- Ammon: Milcom = national god; Rabbah = capital (modern Amman, Jordan); Ammonites
  occupied Israelite territory (Gad) after the northern exile.
- Edom: Teman and Bozrah = major cities; 'clefts of the rock' = likely Petra area;
  Edomite wisdom tradition renowned (Obad 8; Job 2:11 — Eliphaz from Teman); Edom's
  schadenfreude at Jerusalem's fall generated intense prophetic condemnation (Obad, Ps 137).
- Damascus: capital of Aram; Ben-hadad dynasty; fell to Assyria in 732 BCE; by
  Jeremiah's time reduced; the oracle may anticipate Nebuchadnezzar's Syrian campaigns.
- Kedar/Hazor: semi-nomadic Arab tribes east of Israel; 'Hazor' is not the Galilean
  city but a name for Arabian confederacy settlements; Nebuchadnezzar campaigned
  against Arab tribes in 599/598 BCE (Babylonian Chronicles).
- Elam: ancient kingdom east of Babylon (modern Khuzestan/Iran); famous bowmen;
  capital Susa; fell to Assyria under Ashurbanipal (c.647 BCE), later absorbed into
  Persian empire; 'restore Elam' (v.39) fulfilled when Elam became a Persian satrapy.
- Babylon: conquered by Cyrus the Great (539 BCE) — Cyrus Cylinder confirms bloodless
  entry; Herodotus describes Cyrus diverting the Euphrates; Bel/Marduk = supreme
  Babylonian deity; Merathaim = 'double rebellion' (wordplay on Marratu, the sea);
  Pekod = 'punishment' (wordplay on Puqudu, Aramean tribe near Babylon).
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

JER_CONTEXT = {
  "49": {
    "1": "<p>The Oracle Against Ammon opens with a territorial accusation: the Ammonites (<em>Benei Ammon</em>) had occupied the land of Gad (the Transjordanian tribe) after Assyria deported the northern Israelite tribes in 722 BCE. Milcom (<em>Malcam</em>) is the national god of Ammon, related to the divine name Molech. His worship involved child sacrifice (2 Kgs 23:10; Jer 32:35). The question — &apos;Has Israel no heir?&apos; — is a rhetorical challenge: the Ammonite occupation of vacated Israelite land violated the principle that the land belongs to YHWH and his covenant people, not to be permanently absorbed by pagan neighbors. Rabbah of the Ammonites is modern Amman, Jordan — the capital city whose name (<em>rabbah</em> = great/capital) persists in the modern city name.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The war cry (<em>teri&apos;ah</em>) against Rabbah of the Ammonites anticipates its desolation: it will become a <em>tel</em> (ruin-mound), a desolation heap (<em>gal shomemah</em>). <em>Tel</em> is the archaeological term for the layered mound left by successive ancient settlements — the very word used for archaeological tells across the Near East (Tell es-Sultan = Jericho, Tell el-Hesi, etc.). The verse precisely anticipates what happened: ancient Rabbah is buried under layers of occupation. The daughter cities (surrounding settlements) will be burned, and Israel will re-inherit what Ammon took — a reversal of the dispossession named in v. 1.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Heshbon (originally Moabite/Reubenite territory, now near Ammonite borders) is called to wail. <em>Ai</em> here is not the Canaanite Ai of Joshua 7-8 but an Ammonite city in Transjordan. The daughters of Rabbah — surrounding settlements or communities (<em>bat</em> = daughter-city is a standard idiom for dependent settlements) — are told to put on sackcloth. The exile of Ammonite priests and their officials (<em>kohanim and sarim</em>) mirrors the pattern of Judah's own exile: national institutions — priesthood and royal administration — go into exile together. Milcom's exile (his cultic objects and priests removed) means the national deity has been defeated and taken as plunder, the ancient Near Eastern sign of conquest.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The taunt against &apos;the faithless daughter&apos; (<em>habat hashoveivah</em>): Ammon is characterized by a flowing valley (<em>imeqeich zav</em>, perhaps the Jabbok River or the lush Jordan valley agriculture) and by trust in treasures. The accusation — &apos;who will come against me?&apos; — is the hubris of geographic security. Ammon&apos;s position east of Jordan, sheltered by terrain and by relative distance from major invasion routes, bred confidence. The rhetorical answer is: YHWH. National overconfidence rooted in natural advantages rather than covenant relationship is a recurring OAN theme.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Terror brought from all surrounding neighbors: Ammon was surrounded by Moab to the south, Aram to the north, Israel to the west — multiple potential vectors of judgment. The phrase <em>Lord GOD of hosts</em> (<em>Adonai YHWH Tzvaot</em>) combines all three divine names: the covenant name, the divine universal sovereignty, and the cosmic army. <em>Niddach ish lefanav</em> — each one will be driven out straight ahead, with no one to gather the fugitives. The absence of a gatherer/shepherd is the sign of covenant breakdown: the flock scattered with no one to collect it.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The restoration promise for Ammon: <em>ve-acharei-chen ashiv et-shevut benei Ammon</em> (afterward I will restore the fortunes of the Ammonites). The pattern — judgment oracle → qualified restoration promise — appears repeatedly in the OAN section (also 49:39 for Elam; 48:47 for Moab). This does not minimize the judgment but places it within a larger framework: YHWH&apos;s purpose is not permanent erasure of nations but correction and, where possible, restoration. The Ammonites historically survived and are attested through the Persian period.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The Oracle Against Edom opens with a challenge to Teman&apos;s famous wisdom: <em>ha-ein od chokhmah beTeman</em> (is there no longer wisdom in Teman?). Teman was an important Edomite city in the north of Edom (the name means &apos;south&apos; in Hebrew — from the perspective of Israel). The Edomites were renowned for wisdom tradition: Job&apos;s friend Eliphaz is from Teman (Job 2:11); Obadiah 8 also challenges Edom&apos;s sages. The wisdom motif suggests Edom had an intellectual tradition, perhaps connected to its position on trade routes where information from Egypt, Arabia, and Mesopotamia converged. That the wise counselors could not foresee their own destruction is the irony: wisdom that excludes YHWH cannot anticipate YHWH&apos;s actions.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Dedan was an Arabian trading city (modern al-Ula in Saudi Arabia) in communication with Edom along caravan routes. The instruction to &apos;flee into the depths&apos; (<em>amqu lashevet</em>, withdraw to dwell deep) is survival advice — hide from the coming disaster. <em>Eid Esav</em> (the disaster/calamity of Esau) — the time of his punishment has come. This is the Edom = Esau identification that runs through Obadiah and Genesis: Esau is the ancestor of Edom (Gen 36:1, 8), and the Jacob-Esau rivalry becomes the Israel-Edom rivalry. The &apos;time of his visitation&apos; (<em>eit piqadti oto</em>) is the covenantal reckoning: YHWH has scheduled this moment.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The comparison of incomplete gleaning versus total stripping: grape-gatherers leave some gleanings (<em>olelot</em> — the commandment of Lev 19:10 requires leaving gleanings for the poor); thieves steal only enough for their needs. But Edom&apos;s devastation will be total — nothing left. The gleaning-law reference is ironic: Edom will receive no such mercy; not even the minimum left for the poor. The comparison implies that the instrument of judgment will be more thorough than any human thief or harvester.</p>",
    "10": "<p>YHWH himself strips Esau bare (<em>ani chalafti et-Esav</em>, I myself have stripped Esau). The language of stripping/uncovering (<em>chalaf</em>) echoes the imagery of removing a covering: Edom&apos;s hiding places (<em>mistaro</em>) are exposed. His children, brothers, and neighbors are all destroyed — no network of survival. The verse ends: <em>ve-ein hu</em> (and he is no more). Edom&apos;s total erasure is announced. This was historically fulfilled: the Edomites were displaced by Arab pressure in the fifth-fourth centuries BCE, moved into the Negev (becoming Idumeans), and the Nabataean Arabs occupied Petra. The Idumeans were forcibly converted to Judaism by John Hyrcanus in 125 BCE and absorbed into the Jewish people. Edom as a nation ceased to exist.</p>",
    "11": "<p>An unexpected mercy within the judgment oracle: <em>azov yetomecha ani achayyeh uvalmenoticha alay yivtachu</em> (leave your orphans; I will keep them alive; your widows may trust in me). Even within the comprehensive judgment on Edom, YHWH declares himself protector of the most vulnerable — orphans and widows, the social categories without protective male relatives. The verse creates a moral distinction: YHWH destroys Edom&apos;s power structures but protects the powerless. This anticipates the NT pattern of divine judgment that distinguishes between the powerful who relied on self and the vulnerable who relied on God.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The cup of judgment logic: <em>asher ein mishpatam lishtot hakkos shotoh yishtu</em> (those who did not deserve to drink the cup have had to drink it). &apos;Those who did not deserve to drink&apos; refers to Judah — YHWH&apos;s own people who drank the cup of his wrath in the exile. If Judah received judgment despite the covenant, how much more will Edom — without covenant protection — receive judgment? The argument from greater to lesser (qal va-chomer): if the guilty party received judgment, the unpunished party certainly will not escape. Edom will definitely drink.</p>",
    "13": "<p>The divine oath (<em>ki vi nishba&apos;ti</em>, for I have sworn by myself) intensifies the certainty: YHWH swears by himself because there is nothing greater by which to swear (cf. Heb 6:13: &apos;when God made his promise to Abraham ... he swore by himself&apos;). The fate of Bozrah — the major city of Edom (modern Buseirah in Jordan) — is pronounced: desolation, reproach, ruin, curse. Four destruction terms underscore the comprehensiveness. Archaeological surveys of Buseirah confirm major occupation in the Iron Age that ended abruptly, consistent with Jeremiah&apos;s oracle.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The divine messenger sent among the nations (<em>tzir bashulach bagoyim</em>): a herald deployed to gather the nations for war against Edom. This is the divine war council in action — YHWH orders the campaign. The intelligence network of the ancient Near East (trade caravans, merchants) served as a communication system: news of military campaigns spread rapidly. The oracle reflects this: a divine decree goes out that galvanizes coalition forces.</p>",
    "15": "<p><em>Hineh qaton netaticha bagoyim baz ba-adam</em> (I will make you small among the nations, despised among mankind). Edom&apos;s pride (<em>zadon libbecha</em>, the arrogance of your heart, v. 16) is met with the reversal: the nation that thought itself superior becomes the most despised. The elevation of Edom&apos;s physical position (v. 16 — heights and eagle-nests) is the occasion of the fall. Obadiah 3-4 elaborates the same image: &apos;though you soar like the eagle and make your nest among the stars, I will bring you down.&apos;</p>",
    "16": "<p><em>Tiflatecha hissi&apos;ah otach zadon libbecha shoken bechagvei hasela&apos; tofes merom giva</em>: &apos;Your fearsome reputation has deceived you, the arrogance of your heart — O you who dwell in the clefts of the rock and hold the height of the hill.&apos; The &apos;clefts of the rock&apos; (<em>chagvei hasela</em>) is a strong geographical allusion to Petra (Arabic: &apos;rock&apos; = Nabataean Raqmu), Edom&apos;s famous rock-city. The cliff-dwellings and mountain fortresses of Edom&apos;s Transjordanian landscape — including Umm el-Biyara, Sela, and later Petra — gave the Edomites confidence of impregnability. &apos;Though you make your nest as high as the eagle, I will bring you down from there&apos; — the pride of geographic security is named and reversed.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Edom will become a horror (<em>shamma</em>): passersby will be appalled (<em>yishom</em>, hiss) at all its calamities. The public visibility of Edom&apos;s desolation — nations observing and reacting — is the covenant-curse sign of maximal disgrace. The same language appears for Judah/Jerusalem in 18:16; 19:8; 25:9, 11, 18. By applying it to Edom, Jeremiah places the pagan nation under the same covenant-curse framework: YHWH&apos;s judgment on the nations uses the same register as his judgment on his own people.</p>",
    "18": "<p><em>Ke-mahpechat Sedom va-Amorah vishneiha</em>: the Sodom-Gomorrah comparison for Edom. The destroyed cities of the plain (Gen 19) became the biblical shorthand for total divine judgment — no survivors, no settlement, permanent desolation. The comparison invokes both the severity and the moral dimension: Sodom was judged for specific sins (Ezek 16:49-50 adds: pride, excess food, failure to help the poor, and abomination). Applying the Sodom comparison to Edom implies moral equivalence: Edom&apos;s sins of pride and violence against its brother Jacob (cf. Obadiah&apos;s full catalog) rise to the Sodom level.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The lion-from-Jordan image: <em>ke-aryeh ya-aleh migaon haYarden</em> (like a lion coming up from the thickets of the Jordan). The Jordan&apos;s floodplain (<em>gaon haYarden</em>) was dense vegetation where lions sheltered — the lion ascending to higher pasture is an image of irresistible, sudden attack. YHWH compares himself to the lion: he will suddenly rouse Edom and appoint whom he chooses over it. The image of divine appointment — <em>mi bachur elaeiha</em> (who is chosen for her?) — suggests YHWH specifically selects the instrument of Edom&apos;s judgment, as he selected Babylon for Judah. No one can summon him to account: the rhetorical question &apos;who is like me? and who will challenge me? and what shepherd can stand before me?&apos; asserts absolute divine sovereignty in the execution of judgment.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The divine plan (<em>etzat YHWH</em>) against Edom and the divine purposes (<em>machshevotav</em>) against Teman: both terms are the language of divine deliberation and strategy. Edom is not a secondary casualty of geopolitical events — it is a specific object of divine intent. The young (<em>tz&apos;irei hatzon</em>, the lambs of the flock) will be dragged away; their pasture will be appalled at them — the land itself reacting to the destruction, an image of the creation responding to covenant violation (cf. the land vomiting out its inhabitants, Lev 18:28).</p>",
    "21": "<p><em>Miqqol nifalam ra-ashshah ha-aretz tzaaaqah baYam-Suf nishma qolah</em>: the noise of Edom&apos;s fall causes the earth to tremble, and the cry is heard at the Red Sea (Yam Suf). The Red Sea reference is geographically specific: Edom&apos;s territory extended to the Gulf of Aqaba (the eastern arm of the Red Sea; cf. 1 Kgs 9:26 — Solomon&apos;s fleet at Ezion-geber). The trembling earth and far-reaching cry convey the enormity of the fall. A great empire&apos;s collapse reverberates cosmically.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The eagle-swooping image: <em>hineh ke-nesher ya-aleh vidaa</em> (like an eagle ascending and spreading its wings over Bozrah). The Babylonian army swooping over Bozrah like an eagle. The eagle (<em>nesher</em>) was a standard ANE symbol of military power — the Babylonian army used eagle-wing imagery on their battle standards; the Assyrians similarly used winged-bull and eagle iconography. The hearts of Edom&apos;s warriors becoming like the heart of a woman in labor (<em>yom tzarah</em>) is the ancient idiom for panic-induced helplessness: the most fearsome soldiers lose all capacity for courage.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The Oracle Against Damascus opens with the alarm of Hamath and Arpad (major cities of Syria to the north of Damascus). Bad news (<em>shemu-ah ra-ah</em>) has traveled and dismantled their composure. <em>Hamath</em> (modern Hama on the Orontes River) and <em>Arpad</em> (Tell Rif&apos;at, north of Aleppo) were major Syrian cities that had already fallen to Assyria (Hamath in 720 BCE under Sargon II; Arpad in 740 BCE under Tiglath-pileser III). Their mention here suggests the oracle looks at a broader Syrian collapse that includes Damascus. The &apos;anguish like the sea that cannot be quiet&apos; (<em>yam de-agah lo tishqot</em>) uses the sea&apos;s restlessness as an image of uncontainable anxiety.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Damascus grows feeble (<em>raphah Damascus</em>), turns to flee, panic seizes her. The &apos;city of renown&apos; (<em>ir tehillati</em>, city of my joy/praise — YHWH speaking) — Damascus is described with a term of divine affection before its destruction. This unexpected note of divine lament adds pathos: even the condemned city was once the object of divine pleasure. The birth-pangs image (<em>chil keyoleda</em>) appears again — universal ANE metaphor for military helplessness.</p>",
    "25": "<p><em>Eich lo-azuvah ir tehillah qiriyat masoseh</em>: &apos;How is the renowned city not abandoned, the city of my delight!&apos; A difficult verse: is this YHWH lamenting the impending abandonment, or a rhetorical exclamation at its unexpected fall? Damascus was one of the oldest continuously inhabited cities in the world (continuously settled since at least 8000 BCE; mentioned in Egyptian records from the fifteenth century BCE). Its antiquity and prosperity made it seem permanent. The oracle cuts against that assumption: no city is so ancient it cannot be abandoned.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The young men falling in the streets, warriors struck down: the same formula used for Jerusalem&apos;s fall (Lam 2:21) is applied to Damascus. The YHWH-of-hosts formula closes the Damascus oracle. Damascus historically survived but was repeatedly contested — the Babylonians campaigned in Syria in 604-600 BCE; Nebuchadnezzar controlled the region. Damascus did not experience the same total desolation as Edom, but it fell under Babylonian hegemony.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The burning of Damascus&apos;s walls and the palaces of Ben-hadad: Ben-hadad (<em>Bar-Hadad</em> = son of Hadad, the storm-god) was a dynastic name for the kings of Aram-Damascus — there were at least three Ben-hadads in the ninth-eighth centuries BCE (1 Kgs 15:18; 20:1; 2 Kgs 8:7-15). The palaces bear the dynastic name, identifying them as the seat of Aramean royal power. The burning of palaces is the standard mark of conquest in the ancient Near East — the defeat of the royal house and its divine patron.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The Oracle Against Kedar and the kingdoms of Hazor: Nebuchadnezzar is explicitly named as the instrument of judgment. Kedar was a major confederation of Arab tribes from the northern Arabian peninsula, mentioned in Assyrian records as early as the ninth century BCE (the Qidri in the Annals of Tiglath-pileser III). Genesis 25:13 identifies Kedar as a son of Ishmael. <em>Hazor</em> here is not the Galilean Hazor of Joshua 11 but a term for settled Arab communities in the Syro-Arabian desert. The command <em>qum</em> (arise!) addresses the Babylonian army — YHWH mobilizing his instrument.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Their tents and flocks — pastoral property (<em>ohaleihem vetzoneihem</em>) — and their tent-curtains, vessels, and camels will be taken. The specific listing of Kedar&apos;s moveable wealth (tents, flocks, camels — the three pillars of nomadic economy) reflects accurate knowledge of their lifestyle. Camels were the primary capital asset of desert peoples; their loss meant economic ruin. The war cry over them — <em>magor misaviv</em> (terror on every side) — is the signature phrase of Jeremiah (6:25; 20:3, 10; 46:5; 49:29; see also 20:3 where Jeremiah renames Pashhur &apos;Magor-Missabib&apos;).</p>",
    "30": "<p>The Babylonian Chronicles record Nebuchadnezzar&apos;s campaign against Arab tribes in 599/598 BCE (the &apos;Hagarites&apos; campaign in the Chronicles). The command to flee deep into the wilderness is ironic: nomadic peoples who lived in the wilderness as their normal habitat are now told to go even deeper into it for safety. The plan (<em>chashav aleihem etzah</em>) is YHWH&apos;s, executed by Nebuchadnezzar.</p>",
    "31": "<p><em>Qumu alu el-goy shanaen yoshev lavetach</em>: &apos;Rise and advance against a nation living in ease that dwells in security.&apos; The description of the Arab tribes — no gates, no bars, dwelling alone — reflects the nomadic tribal lifestyle: no walls (mobility is their defense), scattered habitation. They had &apos;no gates or bars&apos; (<em>delatayim ubriach</em>) — in contrast to walled cities, their security was openness and mobility. This very quality makes them vulnerable to a concentrated military campaign they cannot wall out.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Their camels — their capital — become plunder; their cattle a spoil. Those who &apos;clip the corners of their hair&apos; (<em>qotztzei pe&apos;ah</em>): this is a specific cultural practice of Arab tribes mentioned in Herodotus (3.8) as distinctive Arabian grooming — they clipped the hair at the temples to honor their god Orotalt. The same practice is mentioned in Jer 9:26 and 25:23 as characterizing peripheral peoples. YHWH will scatter them to all the winds — the four-directional scattering formula (cf. 49:36 for Elam) indicates total dispersal with no remnant gathered together.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Hazor becoming a haunt of jackals (<em>me&apos;on tannim</em>), a desolation forever (<em>shemamah le-olam</em>): the desolation-animal formula (jackals replacing human habitation) appears throughout the OAN section and in the Babylon oracle (50:39; 51:37). Jackals were the scavengers of the desert and ruined places — their presence marks the complete withdrawal of human civilization. The contrast between Kedar&apos;s current nomadic ease (v. 31) and the future jackal-haunted waste is the oracle&apos;s shock.</p>",
    "34": "<p>The Oracle Against Elam: dated to the beginning of Zedekiah&apos;s reign (ca. 598/597 BCE — immediately after Jehoiachin&apos;s exile). Elam was the ancient kingdom centered on Susa (modern Shush in Khuzestan Province, Iran). Its history extended back to the third millennium BCE. Elam was periodically a major power — the Elamites sacked Babylon in 1158 BCE. By Jeremiah&apos;s period, Elam had been devastated by Ashurbanipal of Assyria (ca. 647 BCE) but was recovering. Elamite archers were famous throughout the ancient world: Isa 22:6 mentions Elam&apos;s quiver; the Persian imperial army later relied heavily on Elamite bowmen.</p>",
    "35": "<p><em>Hinneni shover et-qeshet Elam reshit gevuratam</em>: &apos;I am going to break the bow of Elam, the foremost source of their strength.&apos; The bow was Elam&apos;s signature weapon and the basis of their military reputation. Breaking it is not merely military disarmament but the destruction of national identity — a people known by their bow lose their reason for being a warrior-nation. The phrase <em>reshit gevuratam</em> (the foremost source of their strength) is almost &apos;the thing they were best known for.&apos; YHWH identifies and attacks the specific foundation of each nation&apos;s pride: Edom&apos;s wisdom (v. 7), Ammon&apos;s wealth (v. 4), Edom&apos;s geographic security (v. 16), Elam&apos;s bow.</p>",
    "36": "<p>The four winds from the four corners of heaven (<em>arba ruchot mishteih shamayim</em>): a cosmic dispersal. YHWH commands the winds themselves to scatter Elam. This language intensifies the dispersal beyond any human military action: the forces of creation are mobilized. The four-corners-of-heaven formula occurs in Ezek 37:9 (the valley of dry bones vision) and Zech 2:6 (the four winds scattering Israel). The dispersal to every nation, every people — there will be no land where Elamite exiles are not found.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Terror before enemies, disaster brought — <em>charon api</em> (my fierce anger), the burning wrath of YHWH sent against them. The sword after them — judgment that pursues rather than waiting. The sequence: terror (psychological), disaster (social/economic), sword (military) — all three modes of covenant curse (Lev 26; Deut 28). The emphasis is that YHWH himself brings the disaster: not the Babylonian army acting independently but YHWH&apos;s own wrath sent against them.</p>",
    "38": "<p><em>Vesimti kis-i be-Elam</em>: &apos;I will place my throne in Elam.&apos; The divine throne in Elam is the most striking image in this oracle: YHWH establishes his rule in the enemy territory, and from there destroys their king and officials. The throne of YHWH set up in enemy territory symbolizes universal sovereignty — no place is beyond his dominion (cf. Amos 9:2-4: &apos;though they go into captivity before their enemies, there I will command the sword to kill them&apos;). The king (<em>melekh</em>) and his officials are specifically targeted — the leadership structure, not just the population.</p>",
    "39": "<p>The restoration promise for Elam in the latter days (<em>be-acharit hayamim</em>): the same formula as 48:47 (Moab) and 49:6 (Ammon). All three enemy nations in this cluster receive restoration promises. This pattern throughout the OAN reflects the theological principle that YHWH&apos;s judgment is corrective and not merely destructive: the &apos;latter days&apos; restoration encompasses even traditional enemies of Israel. Historically, Elam was absorbed into the Persian empire — and Susa became a royal capital of Persia (Esther 1:2). Elamites were present at Pentecost (Acts 2:9): the eschatological restoration of Elam is there beginning to be realized.</p>"
  },
  "50": {
    "1": "<p>The Great Oracle Against Babylon occupies two full chapters (50-51) — the longest single oracle in the book and arguably the most theologically dense. The superscription: <em>hadavar asher diber YHWH el-Bavel el-eretz Kasdim beyad Yirmiyahu hanavi</em>. The oracle is addressed to Babylon as a whole and to the land of the Chaldeans specifically — the Chaldeans being the ruling Babylonian dynasty (Neo-Babylonian dynasty founded by Nabopolassar in 626 BCE). The prophetic medium is specified: <em>beyad Yirmiyahu</em> (through/by the hand of Jeremiah) — the hand-formula for prophetic transmission emphasizes that this is mediated divine speech.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The proclamation formula to the nations: <em>hagidu vagoyim vehashmi-u</em> (announce and proclaim). Raise the signal banner, proclaim without hiding. What follows is the core announcement: Babylon is taken, Bel is put to shame, Marduk is dismayed, her images are put to shame, her idols are dismayed. Bel (title meaning &apos;lord&apos;) was the title of Marduk, the supreme god of Babylon — the Babylonian national deity who was believed to have given Nebuchadnezzar his victories. <em>Chofer</em> and <em>chatat</em> (shamed and dismayed) — the terms for divine defeat. When Babylon falls, Marduk&apos;s power is refuted. The proclamation to the nations inverts the Babylonian victory announcements that went out when Babylon conquered others.</p>",
    "3": "<p>A nation from the north (<em>goy mitsafon</em>) will come against Babylon and make her land a desolation. The &apos;foe from the north&apos; that Jeremiah repeatedly applied to Babylon itself (1:14; 4:6; 6:22) is now turned against Babylon. The instrument of judgment becomes the object of judgment. Historically, this was fulfilled by Cyrus the Great of Persia (Achaemenid dynasty) who conquered Babylon in 539 BCE — the Persians came from the north and east. The formula &apos;man nor beast will dwell there&apos; (<em>ein yoshev bahem</em>) echoes the desolation pattern applied to Judah in 4:25; now Babylon receives the same.</p>",
    "4": "<p><em>Bayamim hahem uveet hahi neum YHWH yavo-u venei Yisrael hemmah uvnei Yehudah yachdav</em>: &apos;In those days and at that time, declares the LORD, the people of Israel and the people of Judah will come together.&apos; The joint return of northern and southern kingdoms is a recurring restoration promise (3:18; 31:6, 31-34; 33:7). They will weep as they come (<em>haloch vivecheh yelekhu</em>) — penitential tears accompanying the return; and seek YHWH their God. The covenant-seeking formula: the return from exile is not merely geographic but theological — it is the people turning to their God (cf. Deut 30:1-6 where the return from exile is contingent on return to YHWH).</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>Tziyon yish-alu derekh hennah peneihem yilekhu</em>: They will ask the way to Zion with their faces turned toward it. This is the reversal of exile: exile is face-turned-away from Zion (the covenantal geography of presence); return is face-turned-toward Zion. The covenant renewal they seek is described as <em>berit olam</em> (eternal/everlasting covenant) — the phrase that characterizes the new covenant of 31:31-34 and the Davidic covenant of 33:20-21. <em>Lo tishakhach</em> (not to be forgotten) — this covenant is permanent; no future apostasy will annul it. The return from Babylon is the beginning of the fulfillment of the new covenant promise.</p>",
    "6": "<p><em>Tzon ovedet hayu ammi</em>: &apos;My people have been like lost sheep.&apos; The shepherd-and-sheep covenant image runs through Jeremiah: the false shepherds of ch. 23 who led the flock astray; the promise of a good shepherd in 23:4-5. Here, the sheep &apos;wandered from mountain to hill&apos; — the high-place worship that characterized Israel&apos;s apostasy; they &apos;forgot their resting place&apos; (<em>mavtzehem</em>) — the covenantal resting place of YHWH&apos;s presence. Their enemies devoured them without guilt, &apos;because they sinned against the LORD, the true habitation of righteousness, the LORD, the hope of their fathers&apos; (v. 7). The guilt-logic: the nations attacked Israel without their own guilt because Israel&apos;s sin invited the attack.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The enemy&apos;s self-exculpation: <em>lo ne-esham</em> (we are not guilty) — because Israel sinned against YHWH. This is the logic of covenant curse: when YHWH&apos;s people are punished, the nations who execute the judgment can claim they acted under divine sanction. But this logic has limits — the instruments of judgment can themselves be judged for excess or pride (cf. Isa 10:5-15 where Assyria is punished for its arrogance in executing YHWH&apos;s judgment). YHWH, the <em>neveh tzedeq</em> (habitation of righteousness) and <em>mikveh avoteihem</em> (hope of their fathers) — two divine epithets: the place where justice dwells and the object of ancestral hope.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The exodus command: <em>nud mitorev Bavel</em> (flee from the midst of Babylon). Isaiah 48:20 gives the same command: &apos;Come out of Babylon, flee from the Chaldeans.&apos; Rev 18:4 repeats it for the eschatological Babylon: &apos;Come out of her, my people.&apos; The exodus pattern: YHWH&apos;s people are to leave the place of captivity and return to the covenant land — just as the Exodus from Egypt structured the first redemption. The he-goat (<em>ka-ayelim lifnei tzon</em>) image: the lead animal at the front of the flock. The exiles are to take initiative and lead the way out.</p>",
    "9": "<p>An assembly of great nations from the north stirred up against Babylon: the Medo-Persian alliance that Cyrus led was indeed a coalition of peoples. <em>Gedudim</em> (companies/troops) arranged against Babylon. The arrows of the coalition will not miss: <em>lo tashov reyqam</em> (they will not return empty) — a warrior&apos;s arrows hitting their mark. The cosmic precision of divine judgment: the arrows of YHWH&apos;s appointed instrument are guided to their target.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Chaldea as plunder: <em>vehayetah Kasdim leshallal kol sholaleiha yisba-u</em> (Chaldea will become plunder; all who plunder her will be satisfied). The Babylonians who plundered the nations will themselves be plundered — the retributive mirror of covenant justice. The Cyrus Cylinder (539 BCE) describes Cyrus restoring temple treasures to their places: the plunder that Babylon took from the nations was redistributed when Babylon fell. Ezra 1:7-11 records Cyrus returning the temple vessels Nebuchadnezzar had taken from Jerusalem.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The indictment of Babylon&apos;s joy: they &apos;rejoiced and exulted&apos; (<em>samachtem ve-aloztem</em>) as plunderers of YHWH&apos;s inheritance. The heifer-on-grass (<em>ka-eglah doresheh</em>) image depicts unrestrained, carefree joy — the animal sporting in a meadow, free of burden. This unrestrained celebration at Judah&apos;s destruction inverts what Babylon should have felt: any serious engagement with what they had done — destroying YHWH&apos;s city and temple, deporting his people — should have produced sobriety, not exuberance. The neighing (<em>tzahaltun ka-abirim</em>, neighed like stallions) adds the image of full-throated, uncontained pride.</p>",
    "12": "<p><em>Boshah imchem meod chafrah yoladtechem</em>: &apos;Your mother will be utterly ashamed; the one who bore you will be disgraced.&apos; Babylon&apos;s &apos;mother&apos; — the Chaldean dynasty (Nabopolassar, the founder) or the city-goddess — will be put to shame. The end of the verse: <em>acharit goyim midbar tziyah va-aravah</em> (she will become the last of the nations — a wilderness, a dry land, a desert). Three progressively barren terms: wilderness, dry, desert. Babylon&apos;s lush Mesopotamian territory, irrigated by the Euphrates and Tigris, will become like the desert wastelands. Archaeological and geographic surveys confirm that after Alexander&apos;s death and the shift of population to Seleucia, the ancient city of Babylon progressively abandoned and was eventually completely deserted.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Because of YHWH&apos;s wrath (<em>miqetzef YHWH</em>), she will not be inhabited — <em>shemamah kula</em> (completely desolate). The hissing passersby (<em>yishreq</em>) echo the covenant curse formula: Babylon receives the same response from passersby that Jerusalem received (18:16; 19:8). The irony is complete: the nation that gloated over Jerusalem&apos;s fall becomes itself the object of travelers&apos; horrified hissing.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The battle deployment against Babylon: <em>erekhu al-Bavel misaviv</em> (deploy yourselves against Babylon from every side). All who draw the bow — the Persian armies were famous archers (Herodotus describes the Persian-Median archers in detail). The command: &apos;do not spare your arrows&apos; (<em>al tachmosu al chetz</em>). The reason: <em>ki le-YHWH chata-ah</em> (for she has sinned against the LORD). Babylon&apos;s sin is the basis of the military campaign: this is not merely geopolitical conquest but covenant-consequential judgment.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Shout against Babylon from every side — she has surrendered (<em>nattanah yadah</em>, she has given her hand). The surrendered hand is the ANE gesture of submission: a defeated king extended his hand to the victor to receive a cord or chain. Her foundations have fallen (<em>naflu ashuteha</em>): not merely the walls but the deep foundations of Babylonian civilization. <em>Ki niqmat YHWH hi</em>: this is the vengeance of the LORD — the retributive justice that returns on Babylon what it did to others. &apos;As she has done, do to her&apos; is the <em>lex talionis</em> of covenant justice applied to nations.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Cut off the sower and the reaper: the agricultural cycle of Babylon — planting and harvest — is disrupted. The foreign workers flee: <em>mipnei cherev hayonah ish el-ammo yifnu</em> (before the sword of the oppressor, everyone will return to their own people). The foreign labor force — migrants and subjugated peoples working Babylonian fields — disperses at the first sign of military collapse. This was historically accurate: Babylon&apos;s agricultural economy depended on subject peoples; their departure at the Persian conquest accelerated the city&apos;s economic decline.</p>",
    "17": "<p><em>Seh pezurah Yisrael arayot hiddichu</em>: &apos;Israel is a scattered sheep; lions have driven it away.&apos; The scattered-sheep image (50:6) returns. Two sequential predators are named: first the king of Assyria devoured it, last Nebuchadnezzar of Babylon has gnawed his bones. The two-stage destruction of Israel: the Assyrian conquest of the north (722 BCE) and the Babylonian conquest of the south (586 BCE). Both are identified as lions — powerful predators — but both will be punished in turn (v. 18). The chronological sequence (first Assyria, then Babylon) structures Judah&apos;s history within the oracle.</p>",
    "18": "<p><em>Laken koh amar YHWH Tzvaot elohe Yisrael</em>: therefore YHWH will punish the king of Babylon and his land just as he punished the king of Assyria (<em>ka-asher paqadti al melech Ashur</em>). Assyria&apos;s fate is the precedent for Babylon&apos;s. Assyria was destroyed by the Babylonian-Median alliance in 614-612 BCE (fall of Nineveh) and 610-609 BCE (fall of Harran) — within Jeremiah&apos;s lifetime. The same God who brought down Assyria will bring down Babylon. The historical precedent validates the prophetic claim.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The restoration of Israel to its pasture: <em>vehashiboti et-Yisrael el-navehu</em> (I will bring Israel back to his pasture). The geographic specificity — Carmel, Bashan, Ephraim, Gilead — represents all of Israel&apos;s most productive territories. Carmel (fertile coastal range), Bashan (rich tableland east of the Sea of Galilee, famous for cattle — Amos 4:1), Ephraim (the central highlands), Gilead (Transjordanian highlands). <em>Tishba nafsho</em> (his appetite/soul will be satisfied) — the soul-satisfaction formula of Ps 107:9 (&apos;he satisfies the thirsty soul and fills the hungry soul with good things&apos;). Return from exile means complete restoration of the covenant life.</p>",
    "20": "<p><em>Bayamim hahem uveet hahi neum YHWH yevuqqash et-avon Yisrael veeynenu</em>: &apos;In those days and at that time, declares the LORD, Israel&apos;s iniquity will be searched for, but there will be none, and the sins of Judah will not be found; for I will forgive those I spare.&apos; This is the most comprehensive forgiveness formula in Jeremiah — total iniquity-erasure. The connection to 31:34 (&apos;I will forgive their iniquity and remember their sin no more&apos;) is explicit: the new covenant promise of complete forgiveness, applied to the restoration from Babylon as its initial fulfillment. The search for iniquity yields nothing — it has been expunged. NT application: 1 John 1:9 (&apos;he is faithful and just to forgive us our sins and to cleanse us from all unrighteousness&apos;) and Heb 10:17-18 (&apos;their sins and their lawless acts I will remember no more&apos;).</p>",
    "21": "<p>Merathaim and Pekod: two geographic locations with Hebrew wordplay. <em>Merathaim</em> (double rebellion/bitterness) is a wordplay on <em>Marratu</em>, the Babylonian name for the marshy area at the confluence of the Tigris and Euphrates (the Persian Gulf region). <em>Pekod</em> (visitation/punishment) is a wordplay on <em>Puqudu</em>, an Aramean tribe in southern Babylonia. The puns make the oracle&apos;s meaning visible in the geography: YHWH has built judgment into the very names of Babylon&apos;s territories. <em>Cherem</em> (complete destruction/ban): the same term used for holy war in Joshua — the Canaanites were devoted to <em>cherem</em> destruction; now Babylon receives the same designation.</p>",
    "22": "<p><em>Qol milchamah ba-aretz veshever gadol</em>: the sound of battle and great destruction. The two terms — sound of battle (<em>qol milchamah</em>) and great destruction (<em>shever gadol</em>) — are the two dimensions of the fall: the audible chaos of combat and the visible wreckage left behind. The compressed brevity of the verse (five Hebrew words) is itself expressive: the disaster arrives with blunt, sudden force.</p>",
    "23": "<p><em>Eikh niqqatz veyishaver pattish kol-ha-aretz</em>: &apos;How the hammer of the whole earth has been cut to pieces and broken!&apos; Babylon as the hammer of the whole earth (<em>pattish kol-ha-aretz</em>) — YHWH&apos;s instrument for striking the nations (cf. 51:20-23 where Babylon is &apos;my war club&apos; and &apos;weapon of war&apos;). The hammer is now broken: the instrument that was used to beat others is itself beaten. The exclamation <em>eikh</em> (how!) is the lament particle of Lamentations 1:1 (&apos;How lonely sits the city&apos;). Even Babylon&apos;s fall elicits something like lament at the magnitude of what has happened.</p>",
    "24": "<p><em>Yaqoshti lach vegam nillakhat Bavel</em>: &apos;I laid a snare for you and you were caught, O Babylon, before you knew it.&apos; The divine hunter who sets snares (cf. 5:26 where the wicked of Israel set snares for men; now YHWH sets the snare for Babylon). The surprise of capture — <em>lo yadata</em> (before you knew it) — reflects the historical suddenness of Babylon&apos;s fall: according to Herodotus and the Nabonidus Chronicle, Cyrus entered Babylon in 539 BCE while Belshazzar held a feast (Dan 5). The reason: <em>ki el-YHWH higgarat</em> (because you strove against the LORD). Striving against YHWH is the fundamental category of Babylonian sin — not merely political overreach but ontological hubris.</p>",
    "25": "<p>YHWH has opened his armory (<em>pithach YHWH et-otzaro</em>) and brought out the weapons of his anger (<em>kele za-amo</em>). The divine armory is the arsenal of cosmic warfare — the divine warrior&apos;s weapons. The work of the Lord GOD of hosts is in the land of the Chaldeans — the phrase <em>melechet Adonai YHWH Tzvaot</em> (the work of the Lord GOD of hosts) frames Babylon&apos;s destruction as a divine project, not a human military achievement. Cyrus is the instrument; YHWH is the agent.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The siege commands: attack from every end (<em>miqetz ba-u lah</em>), open her granaries (<em>pitchu mizbanoieha</em>), pile her up like heaps (<em>soluha ka-aremim</em>), completely destroy her, let nothing remain. The granary-opening image: Babylon&apos;s immense grain stores (Herodotus describes Babylon&apos;s twenty-year food supply) are opened for plunder. The heap-image (<em>aremim</em>): grain heaps, but also ruin-mounds — <em>tel</em>. Both meanings converge: the grain stores become ruins.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Slaughter all her bulls — her military leadership, the most powerful men. The bovine metaphor for warriors (cf. Ps 22:12: &apos;strong bulls of Bashan surround me&apos;) is standard ANE imagery. The killing ground (<em>yedu latebach</em>, go down to the slaughter) echoes the sacrifice-slaughter image. <em>Oi lahem ki va yomam eit piqudatam</em>: Woe to them, for their day has come — the time of their reckoning. <em>Eit piqudat</em> is the appointed-time-of-visitation formula: the date for covenant reckoning was set in YHWH&apos;s calendar before Babylon ever conquered Judah.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Those who flee from Babylon declare YHWH&apos;s vengeance in Zion: <em>mesha-eim uferiteimim me-eretz Bavel lehagid beTziyon et-niqmat YHWH</em>. The fugitives&apos; proclamation of YHWH&apos;s vengeance in Zion serves an apologetic purpose: the destruction of Babylon is declared to be specifically about the temple. <em>Niqmat heichalo</em> (vengeance for his temple): the burning of the temple in 586 BCE is the specific grievance; Babylon&apos;s fall is YHWH vindicating his own house. The theme of temple-vengeance grounds the geopolitical event in covenant theology.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Archers summoned against Babylon: encamp all around, let none escape, give her according to her work (<em>shalem la kema-aseiha</em>), act to her according to all she has done (<em>kekol asher-asatah asu lah</em>). The proportionality principle: Babylon receives exactly what she gave. The specific provocation: <em>ki el-YHWH zadah</em> (for she has acted arrogantly against the LORD), against the Holy One of Israel. The title <em>qadosh Yisrael</em> (Holy One of Israel) is characteristic of Isaiah (used 26 times in Isa 1-66) but appears here in Jeremiah — the rarity marks the intensity of the theological claim: Babylon has offended YHWH&apos;s holiness itself.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Young men fallen in the streets, warriors silenced: the standard formula of city-fall applied to Babylon (cf. Lam 2:21; Jer 49:26; 50:30). The repetition across the oracles against multiple nations establishes a pattern: YHWH&apos;s judgment formula is consistently applied regardless of which nation receives it. The universality of the judgment pattern — no city exempt — is itself the theological point.</p>",
    "31": "<p><em>Hinneni eleicha zadon</em>: &apos;Behold, I am against you, O most arrogant.&apos; <em>Zadon</em> (arrogance/pride) is personified as Babylon itself — the empire is its arrogance. The divine adversative (<em>hinneni eleicha</em>) appears throughout Jeremiah as the covenant lawsuit formula for divine opposition. The time has come: <em>ki va yomcha eit piqadticha</em> (your day has come, the time I will punish you). YHWH appointed the time of Babylon&apos;s punishment before it happened — the oracle was given decades before Cyrus.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The most arrogant will stumble and fall (<em>ve-kashel ve-nafal hazadon</em>) — no one to raise him up. The sequence of stumbling and falling is the same vocabulary used for Israel&apos;s fall in Amos 5:2 (&apos;fallen, no more to rise, is the virgin Israel&apos;). The same fate now comes to the empire that caused Israel to fall. Fire set to Babylon&apos;s cities consuming all around: the burning of cities is the standard conquest-conclusion in the ancient Near East (the Lachish reliefs of Sennacherib show Assyrian fires consuming Judean cities).</p>",
    "33": "<p>The shared oppression: <em>koh amar YHWH Tzvaot ashukot benei Yisrael uvnei Yehudah yachdav</em> (the people of Israel are oppressed, and the people of Judah with them). All their captors hold them fast (<em>kol shoveichem hecheziku vam</em>) and refuse to release them (<em>me-anu shalacham</em>). The legal-rescue framing: YHWH as the kinsman-redeemer (<em>go-el</em>) who pleads the cause of the held-captive. The captors&apos; refusal to release triggers the goel&apos;s action: when human captors will not release, the divine redeemer acts directly.</p>",
    "34": "<p><em>Go-alam chazaq YHWH Tzvaot shemo riv yariv et-rivam</em>: &apos;Their Redeemer is mighty; the LORD of hosts is his name. He will certainly plead their cause.&apos; The <em>go-el</em> (kinsman-redeemer) title for YHWH: in Israelite law, the <em>go-el</em> was the nearest male relative who had the right and obligation to redeem a family member from slavery, avenge his blood, or redeem mortgaged family land. YHWH is the ultimate <em>go-el</em> (cf. Isa 43:14; 44:6, 24; 47:4; 48:17 where &apos;go-el&apos; is a major Isaiah title for YHWH). The strongest kinsman who owes redemption-loyalty will act — Babylon has enslaved what belongs to him.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The sword litany begins: <em>cherev al-Kasdim</em> (a sword against the Chaldeans). The sequence of sword-against in vv. 35-38 is a poem — seven recipients of the sword: inhabitants of Babylon (v. 35), officials and wise men (v. 35), false prophets (v. 36), warriors (v. 36), horses and chariots (v. 37), foreign troops (v. 37), treasures (v. 37), waters (v. 38). The comprehensiveness maps every component of Babylonian power. The prophets and wise men (<em>chakhameha</em>) — Babylon&apos;s divination establishment (the <em>baru</em> priests, astrologers, omen-readers) were famous throughout the ancient world; Daniel 1:20 notes the Babylonian wise men&apos;s status at court. Their sword-judgment means Babylon&apos;s intelligence apparatus will fail.</p>",
    "36": "<p>A sword against her false prophets (<em>badim</em>, diviners/liars) — they will become fools (<em>venoallu</em>). The Hebrew <em>badim</em> refers specifically to false prophets or diviners; the root suggests those who speak empty or false words. Babylon&apos;s religious-political prophecy establishment — which consistently predicted Babylonian invincibility — will be exposed as foolish when the empire falls. A sword against her warriors, so they become dismayed: the military elite who formed Babylon&apos;s professional army (the <em>gabbe</em> soldiers) will lose heart.</p>",
    "37": "<p>A sword against her horses and chariots: the chariot corps was Babylon&apos;s mechanized warfare. A sword against the foreign troops (<em>ha-erev</em>): the mixed multitude of mercenaries and subject-peoples in Babylon&apos;s army. They will become like women (<em>vehaytem lanashim</em>) — the idiom for complete loss of martial courage (cf. Isa 19:16; Nah 3:13). A sword against her treasures: the immense wealth of Babylon — plundered from nations, hoarded in temples and palaces — becomes subject to plunder itself.</p>",
    "38": "<p>A drought upon her waters: <em>chorev al-meiha veyvoshu</em> (drought upon her waters and they will dry up). This is wordplay: <em>cherev</em> (sword) in vv. 35-37 shifts to <em>chorev</em> (drought/heat) in v. 38 — the two words differ only in vocalization. The Euphrates and its canals were the lifeblood of Babylon; Cyrus&apos;s strategy according to Herodotus involved diverting the Euphrates to allow his troops to enter through the dry riverbed. The drying of the waters is both literal (the military tactic) and theological (YHWH withdrawing the life-support of Babylon). <em>Ki eretz pesilim hi</em> (for it is a land of idols) — the worship of images (<em>pesilim</em>) is the spiritual root of Babylon&apos;s judgment.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Wild desert creatures and jackals will inhabit Babylon; ostriches will live there. The three desolation-animals (demons of the wilderness, jackals, ostriches) appear in the similar desolation oracles of Isa 13:21-22 and 34:13-15 — standard ancient Near Eastern imagery for the complete withdrawal of human civilization and its replacement by the creatures of uninhabited waste. <em>Lo-teshev la-netzach</em> (she shall never again be inhabited) — the permanent desolation formula. Archaeological evidence: after Alexander the Great&apos;s death, plans to rebuild Babylon were abandoned; the city was progressively deserted as population moved to Seleucia on the Tigris. By the first century CE, Babylon was a ruin inhabited by Parthian soldiers.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The Sodom-Gomorrah comparison applied to Babylon: the same comparison made for Edom (49:18) now describes Babylon. Both Edom and Babylon receive the ultimate judgment-type — complete, permanent, uninhabitable. The repetition reinforces that Jeremiah applies the same theological framework to all the nations: YHWH&apos;s judgment on pagan powers uses the Sodom-Gomorrah template as its benchmark. <em>Lo yeshev sham ish</em> (no man will dwell there): the formula of absolute desolation that applies to both individuals and communities.</p>",
    "41": "<p>A people coming from the north — a great nation, many kings roused from the ends of the earth. The Medo-Persian coalition: Cyrus united the Medes (who had destroyed Nineveh in 612 BCE), the Persians, and allied peoples from across the Iranian plateau. <em>Yaqitzu</em> (roused): the awakening-of-kings image suggests divine mobilization — YHWH rousing the nations as his instruments, as he roused Nebuchadnezzar against Judah (1:15; 5:15-17).</p>",
    "42": "<p>They hold bow and spear; cruel, showing no mercy. Their roaring like the sea (<em>yish-agu kayam</em>): the coalition army&apos;s voice fills the land like the surf — overwhelming, constant, irresistible. On horses, arrayed like a man for battle against Babylon. The Persian-Median horse cavalry was formidable; the royal Persian Immortals (10,000 elite troops) were the most professional army of their era. The same phrase that Jeremiah used to describe the Babylonian threat against Judah (6:23: &apos;they are cruel and show no mercy; their voice roars like the sea&apos;) is now applied to the threat against Babylon.</p>",
    "43": "<p>The king of Babylon hears the report and his hands go limp: the same reaction that Zedekiah and the kings of Judah had when they heard of Babylon&apos;s advance. The reversal is exact and deliberate: the empire that caused Judah&apos;s kings to tremble will itself tremble. <em>Chil kayoleda</em> (anguish like a woman in labor): the universal ANE image for paralytic fear. Nebuchadnezzar — or his successors — the great conqueror, reduced to childbirth-pain helplessness.</p>",
    "44": "<p>The lion-from-Jordan image that was used for YHWH against Edom (49:19) now appears against Babylon. The repetition of the image frames the OAN section as a unified whole: YHWH uses the same hunting strategy against all the nations. The rhetorical question — who is appointed over Babylon? — has a clear answer: YHWH himself. He will appoint his chosen one over her. Historically, YHWH&apos;s chosen one for this task was Cyrus — explicitly named in Isa 44:28 and 45:1 as YHWH&apos;s anointed and his shepherd.</p>",
    "45": "<p><em>Lachen shim-u etzat YHWH asher ya-atz el-Bavel umachshevotav asher chashav el-eretz Kasdim</em>: hear the strategy of YHWH against Babylon and his purposes against the Chaldeans. The young of the flock (<em>tz-irei hatzon</em>) will be dragged away — the same phrase used for Edom (49:20). The pasture-horror: <em>asham aleihem naveihem</em> (their pasture will be appalled at them). YHWH&apos;s plan is fixed and announced ahead of time: prophecy is the advance announcement of history from the divine council.</p>",
    "46": "<p>At the sound of Babylon&apos;s capture the earth will quake (<em>tera-ash ha-aretz</em>); the cry will be heard among the nations (<em>yishama bagoyim za-aqatah</em>). The cosmic scale of Babylon&apos;s fall: the earth itself shakes. The Babylonian empire was the dominant power for seventy years — its fall in 539 BCE was a seismic geopolitical event whose reverberations were felt throughout the ancient Near East. The cry heard among the nations is the inverse of v. 2&apos;s proclamation: the announcement goes out to the nations that the empire which had dominated them is ended. Rev 18:9-10, 18-19 uses these images for the eschatological fall of Babylon: kings of the earth weeping, crying &apos;woe, woe for the great city&apos; when they see her smoke rising.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', 'jeremiah')
    merge_comm(existing, JER_CONTEXT)
    save_comm('mkt-context', 'jeremiah', existing)

    out = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/commentary/mkt-context/jeremiah.json').read_text())
    il  = json.loads((ROOT / 'data/interlinear/jeremiah.json').read_text())

    all_ok = True
    for ch in [49, 50]:
        ck = str(ch)
        missing = set(il.get(ck, {}).keys()) - set(out.get(ck, {}).keys())
        if missing:
            print(f'ch {ch} STILL MISSING: {sorted(missing, key=int)}')
            all_ok = False
        else:
            print(f'ch {ch}: complete ({len(out.get(ck, {}))} verses)')
    if all_ok:
        print('All verses present')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
